1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:14,000
The way that I like to work if it's okay with you is I work pretty chronologically.

3
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:21,000
I always think that the work that people end up doing in their lives is always shaped by their families

4
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:24,000
and where they come from and the communities and what they raised and all of that.

5
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:30,000
So I take a pretty, you know, traditional family history approach, at least to where we start.

6
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:31,000
That sounds good.

7
00:00:31,000 --> 00:00:43,000
Great. And then, and certainly in your case, there's, I don't know, there'll be a lot of rich, relevant memories that pertinent to this ill-orice movement.

8
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:45,000
We'll talk about other things as well.

9
00:00:45,000 --> 00:00:54,000
And then, and then carry on through your life into your, your own career and where you see these themes sort of playing out.

10
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Okay.

11
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:56,000
If that sounds good to you.

12
00:00:56,000 --> 00:00:57,000
Sounds good.

13
00:00:57,000 --> 00:01:01,000
It's really, it's your interview, you're in charge, you want to take a break at any point.

14
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:05,000
If you want to take it in a completely different direction, it's up to you.

15
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:06,000
We're very informal in that way.

16
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:07,000
Okay.

17
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:09,000
And we would really want you to be in charge of where we go.

18
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Sounds good.

19
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:13,000
I also try to keep us all on track.

20
00:01:13,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Yeah, we usually go.

21
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:19,000
They vary from 40 minutes, 45 minutes or so to two hours.

22
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:22,000
But, you know, as much time as you want to give us.

23
00:01:22,000 --> 00:01:25,000
And I think we're good for time in terms of our flight and all of that.

24
00:01:25,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Okay.

25
00:01:26,000 --> 00:01:27,000
Great.

26
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:33,000
What I'll do first is just record a little opening message for the file so that we know where we were and when.

27
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:35,000
And then we'll start having a conversation.

28
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:36,000
Sounds good.

29
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:37,000
Thank you.

30
00:01:37,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Oh, with all of that.

31
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:40,000
Okay.

32
00:01:40,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Great.

33
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,000
So today is August 17, 2013.

34
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:46,000
We are in Richmond, Virginia.

35
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:52,000
My name is David Cline from the Department of History at Virginia Tech in Blacksburg.

36
00:01:52,000 --> 00:01:57,000
Also working with the Southern Oral History Program (SOHP) at UNC Chapel Hill.

37
00:01:57,000 --> 00:02:05,000
We are here today for the Civil Rights History Project with the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture.

38
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:10,000
Behind the camera is John Bishop.

39
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:17,000
And we are very pleased to be here today with Oliver W. Hill Jr in Richmond and good morning.

40
00:02:17,000 --> 00:02:18,000
Good morning.

41
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:20,000
And thank you so much for being part of this project.

42
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:21,000
I'm pleasure.

43
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:22,000
Okay.

44
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:23,000
Great. Thank you.

45
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:27,000
So what we'll do is we'll just start by talking a bit about your childhood and your family.

46
00:02:27,000 --> 00:02:28,000
Okay.

47
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:30,000
And then we'll have a good conversation going forward.

48
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:31,000
Okay.

49
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:36,000
So you could tell us when you were born and where and a little bit about the community in which you were raised.

50
00:02:36,000 --> 00:02:37,000
Okay.

51
00:02:37,000 --> 00:02:40,000
I was born in 1949 in Richmond, Virginia.

52
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:45,000
And of course in those days, Richmond was a very segregated community.

53
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:54,000
So I was born in the Black Hospital, which now is a dorm at Virginia Union University.

54
00:02:55,000 --> 00:03:00,000
And in those days, the Black community was its own circumscribed world.

55
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:05,000
I mean, you really didn't have to go outside of it if you didn't want to.

56
00:03:05,000 --> 00:03:09,000
The pharmacy was down the street in the restaurants.

57
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:13,000
We had the same neighborhood and you kind of circled in that neighborhood.

58
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:21,000
And that was kind of the hub of my life for the first 12 years or so that that was alive.

59
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:24,000
Were there certain six years within that community?

60
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:31,000
Certain people who had that were sort of heads of the community or certain businesses that were the center of life?

61
00:03:31,000 --> 00:03:36,000
I mean, one of the things that was interesting was that the neighborhoods were very heterogeneous.

62
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:40,000
You know, you would have a lawyer next to a construction worker, next to a plumber.

63
00:03:40,000 --> 00:03:47,000
So in terms of class, you had much more integration than you do today.

64
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:56,000
And again, because there were so many restrictions on where you could go and where you couldn't go,

65
00:03:56,000 --> 00:04:03,000
you know, there were industries and commercial organizations to take care of whatever needs you had in the community.

66
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:08,000
So in those, in that sense, it was a very self-contained kind of community.

67
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:17,000
And my family was a typical in one sense of that.

68
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:22,000
My father was a civil rights attorney and so he was traveling a lot.

69
00:04:22,000 --> 00:04:29,000
And he was involved with cases from the NAACP Legal Defense Fund.

70
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:35,000
We, as a result, we would have a lot of threats coming in over the telephone.

71
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:39,000
And so I wasn't allowed to answer the phone for a long time in the evenings.

72
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:42,000
We even had a cross-brandon I got at one time.

73
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:43,000
Do you remember that?

74
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:49,000
Yeah, I was probably about six or seven, you know, it was exciting.

75
00:04:50,000 --> 00:04:58,000
I mean, my parents had consciously tried to kind of build up my sense of self.

76
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:10,000
And so that I would be shielded a little bit from the racism and the kinds of reprisals and repercussions that were coming from my father's work.

77
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:18,000
And also, I think they also figured that I was going to be in the group that desegregated schools in Richmond.

78
00:05:18,000 --> 00:05:20,000
And I was.

79
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:28,000
So there was an attempt to try to inculcate in me the idea that prejudice was somebody else's problem.

80
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:35,000
It was an indication of their pathology, not my pathology.

81
00:05:35,000 --> 00:05:37,000
And that worked to a certain extent.

82
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:49,000
Although I'm looking back on growing up in the 50s, I mean, the all white world that you have seen on the television and the media definitely had an effect on me.

83
00:05:49,000 --> 00:05:55,000
I mean, when I would color in a coloring book, I would never think about coloring somebody skinned brown.

84
00:05:55,000 --> 00:05:58,000
Because the norm was white.

85
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:02,000
You know, I wanted wavy hair like Elvis Presley.

86
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:06,000
So those kinds of marks were definitely there.

87
00:06:06,000 --> 00:06:17,000
But I did have a good sense of self and my parents had done a good job in protecting me on that level.

88
00:06:17,000 --> 00:06:23,000
Well, you mentioned Elvis Presley and those kinds of things that were happening psychologically.

89
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:26,000
Did you have other heroes as a kid?

90
00:06:26,000 --> 00:06:35,000
Well, I mean, most of the heroes that I was exposed to in TV and comic books and things were white.

91
00:06:35,000 --> 00:06:40,000
So I was kind of a typical kid on that level.

92
00:06:40,000 --> 00:06:43,000
They really wasn't a real push for black history at that time.

93
00:06:43,000 --> 00:06:46,000
So I really hadn't been exposed to a lot of black heroes.

94
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:53,000
Although my parents had always talked to me about heroes of the black experience.

95
00:06:53,000 --> 00:06:56,000
There wasn't a lot of written material on that.

96
00:06:56,000 --> 00:07:01,000
They would tell me about it and conversations around it in the table.

97
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:03,000
And I was the only child.

98
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:15,000
So they did include me in their discussions, you know, for the most part, about issues of segregation and politics and anything else that might be happening around that time.

99
00:07:15,000 --> 00:07:18,000
Could you tell us a little bit more about who your parents were,

100
00:07:18,000 --> 00:07:23,000
what their backgrounds were, and how they came to be doing that work?

101
00:07:23,000 --> 00:07:29,000
My father was also born in Richmond in 1907.

102
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:33,000
And early on he moved to Roanoke.

103
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:37,000
His father kind of deserted the family early on.

104
00:07:37,000 --> 00:07:39,000
So he was being raised by his mother.

105
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:48,000
And in Roanoke she would go for seasonal work up to places like,

106
00:07:48,000 --> 00:08:00,000
what's the name of the resort hotel's out there drawing a blank The Homestead + The Greenbrier.

107
00:08:00,000 --> 00:08:13,000
And so he was kind of put in this foster home of this middle class family in Roanoke who did a lot of raising of him during those early years.

108
00:08:13,000 --> 00:08:16,000
Name the Pentecost.

109
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:18,000
And Mr. Black family.

110
00:08:18,000 --> 00:08:33,000
But Mr. Pentecost was a very, I don't know, well read, well spoken, very stern kind of person who worked on the railroads.

111
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:39,000
And my father was, you know, kind of living in that environment.

112
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:43,000
I think that had a big influence on his early years.

113
00:08:43,000 --> 00:08:51,000
And my grandmother remarried and eventually moved to Washington with her new husband.

114
00:08:51,000 --> 00:09:00,000
And so my father stayed in Roanoke until he was ready to enter high school because at that time there were no black high schools in Roanoke.

115
00:09:00,000 --> 00:09:02,000
None.

116
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:07,000
So he then went to Washington for high school.

117
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:16,000
And he went to a high school named Dunbar, which was very prestigious high school in those days.

118
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:23,000
It was said to have more PhDs on the high school faculty than some of the colleges in the area.

119
00:09:23,000 --> 00:09:27,000
Which is actually not a typical of black schools in the era.

120
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:28,000
Right.

121
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:29,000
It's true.

122
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:38,000
So he had a great experience at Dunbar and kind of got his academic footing.

123
00:09:38,000 --> 00:09:45,000
But he was still kind of a devil-may-care type personality.

124
00:09:45,000 --> 00:09:48,000
But he decided he was going to go to college.

125
00:09:48,000 --> 00:10:00,000
And before that, his, one of his uncles had worked in a law office and gave him a copy of an annotated constitution.

126
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:07,000
And he said in reading that he couldn't understand why segregation laws were constitutional.

127
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:11,000
And this is really what inspired him to go into law school.

128
00:10:11,000 --> 00:10:17,000
So there was a convergence of things happening at that time at Howard in the late 1920s.

129
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:25,000
There was a president there, Mordecai Wyatt Johnson, who was interested in producing a type flight law school.

130
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:30,000
At that time, Howard's law school was just a night school.

131
00:10:30,000 --> 00:10:40,000
But he brought in a dean from, who had just got his PhD in law from Harvard, named Charles Hamilton Houston.

132
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:52,000
And so Mordecai Wyatt Johnson and Houston kind of molded the faculty in the organization of this law school.

133
00:10:52,000 --> 00:11:02,000
And so Howard also had a program where you could do three years of undergraduate and then go to law school and get your bachelor's degree after the first year in law school.

134
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:06,000
This is my father took advantage of that.

135
00:11:06,000 --> 00:11:13,000
And one of his classmates was Thurgood Marshall, who had been turned down from going to University of Maryland law school.

136
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:16,000
So he was there for that reason.

137
00:11:16,000 --> 00:11:27,000
And they said the first day in class, Charles Hamilton Houston told him that, you know, as lawyers, you're either a social parasite or you're a social engineer.

138
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:32,000
And he was determined they were going to become social engineers.

139
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:50,000
And from that very first year in that first class, Charles Hamilton Houston was kind of guiding the strategy of attacking segregation, mainly in the form of a Plessy v. Ferguson, which was a Supreme Court case that established separate but equal.

140
00:11:50,000 --> 00:12:01,000
My father tells the story that in that time when he was in college in the 1920s, you couldn't even get a law passed against lynching because of the power of the Southern block in Congress.

141
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:09,000
And so that was one of the things that convinced him that it would take something going to the Supreme Court to make a real change.

142
00:12:09,000 --> 00:12:13,000
And so that was part of his motivation as well.

143
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:21,000
So when he got out of law school in 1933, he went Roanoke.

144
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:31,000
But this was middle of depression. And he was having a hard time making an living. So he started waiting tables to earn money.

145
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:50,000
But at the same time, and I can't remember the name of the person, but there was a white individual from a wealthy family who gave a large donation to the NAACP was used to kind of

146
00:12:50,000 --> 00:13:12,000
bankroll the NAACP Legal Defense Fund. And so Charles Hamilton Houston and Thurgood Marshall and my father and several other lawyers were working with NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund (LDF), founded 1940 by Thurgood Marshall.

147
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:16,000
So did the NAACP they called on your father to get going?

148
00:13:16,000 --> 00:13:26,000
Well, I mean, there was this close circle of black looks, almost all of them were Howard graduates. So they all knew each other. And so they all continued to work together.

149
00:13:26,000 --> 00:13:39,000
So Howard really, the Howard Law School under Houston, I mean, that was one of these key places in your opinion where the NAACP-LDF.

150
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:58,000
And it was a conscious effort on the part of Houston and Mordecai Wyatt Johnson to do this. So in the 1930s, one of the first big cases that they had some success with was the school salary case.

151
00:13:58,000 --> 00:14:07,000
I mean, the teacher salary case in Virginia. And those days, the highest pay, black teacher had to make less than the lowest pay, why teach it.

152
00:14:07,000 --> 00:14:19,000
So that was kind of an easy case to take. Although it took several years before it was filing resolved and it was in the 1940s, I think it was filing resolved.

153
00:14:19,000 --> 00:14:29,000
But my father, you know, started working in Virginia and by this time he had moved back to Richmond.

154
00:14:29,000 --> 00:14:39,000
And then he was in his 40s, but he got drafted for World War II. And he thinks it was kind of a conscious decision about the local draft boy.

155
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:53,000
He's trying to get him out of their hair. But once he got in the army, he got to the level of sergeant. He kept pressing for them to send him to Officer Training School as a lawyer.

156
00:14:53,000 --> 00:14:58,000
And they would usually transfer him somewhere else before they got to that point.

157
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:04,000
So yeah, here's this guy with a law degree and they're not taking advantage of that at all.

158
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:16,000
And even in England, he was, again, kicking up a fuss about getting to Officer Canada's school. And that actually caused his unit to be a little bit late.

159
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:22,000
And otherwise, he probably would have been in D-Day, but his unit came up a little bit later.

160
00:15:23,000 --> 00:15:26,000
And he was serving in an all-black unit?

161
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:28,000
Yes, in England.

162
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:31,000
Right. And then into France.

163
00:15:31,000 --> 00:15:41,000
Then when he came back from the war, he started getting involved with local politics here in Richmond.

164
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:50,000
He was one of the first blacks. I guess he was the first black to be elected to an office in the deep south since reconstruction.

165
00:15:50,000 --> 00:15:56,000
He was elected to the Richmond City Council.

166
00:15:56,000 --> 00:16:00,000
Do you remember anything about that campaign?

167
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:03,000
Well, that was before I was born.

168
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:11,000
But he did have several other campaigns after I was born and I do remember those.

169
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:24,000
He ran for House of delegates and lost by 40 votes, I think, or some really close race in the early 50s.

170
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:31,000
But he was always involved in the Virginia Democratic Party.

171
00:16:31,000 --> 00:16:38,000
And even when he was running for City Council, he didn't just confine his race to the black community.

172
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:43,000
He would go around to white communities, knock on doors and ask them for their vote.

173
00:16:43,000 --> 00:16:47,000
So he was always kind of fearless in that way.

174
00:16:47,000 --> 00:16:56,000
And he always attended every meeting, any kind of political thing that was going on in Richmond, it didn't matter whether it was conservative or liberal.

175
00:16:56,000 --> 00:17:01,000
He would be there, if I was in his opinion.

176
00:17:01,000 --> 00:17:09,000
And of course, all this time they were continuing with this strategy of overturning Plessy.

177
00:17:09,000 --> 00:17:20,000
And they finally found some cases that they thought were going to be the ones they needed, particularly Clarendon County.

178
00:17:20,000 --> 00:17:26,000
And it was around that time that he got a call from Barbara Rose Johns in Farmville.

179
00:17:26,000 --> 00:17:35,000
And of course, they were planning to have this boycott of a walk out of their school because of the conditions.

180
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:42,000
And just for the record, for those who don't or are new to this history, could you tell us a little bit about who Barbara Rose Johns was and what was going on in Farmville?

181
00:17:42,000 --> 00:17:47,000
Yeah, well, Barbara Rose Johns was a high school girl.

182
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:54,000
And the black high school in Farmville was a really bad condition.

183
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:03,000
And I think tar paper shacks for some of the overflow and rain would come in.

184
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:07,000
And they would have dripping water on their desks.

185
00:18:07,000 --> 00:18:15,000
Anyway, Barbara Rose Johns kind of organized the students to come up with a protest.

186
00:18:15,000 --> 00:18:21,000
And they were going to have a walk out and refuse to go back until the conditions had changed.

187
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:35,000
And she called my father to come and represent them because the school board was, you know, upset about all this.

188
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:41,000
And their parents were upset because, you know, they were kind of in precarious positions.

189
00:18:41,000 --> 00:18:53,000
And at this time, my father, you know, they kind of had their plates full, particularly, and they thought they had all the cases they needed for this push to the Supreme Court.

190
00:18:53,000 --> 00:19:00,000
But Barbara Rose Johns was so persistent and so organized that he just couldn't resist him.

191
00:19:00,000 --> 00:19:06,000
So they decided to come at least visit Farmville and talk to the parents.

192
00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:10,000
And by this time, they had started to change their strategy.

193
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:16,000
When they first started attacking segregation, they were on the basis of separate but equal.

194
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:23,000
And no southern state had the resources to have completely equal educational facilities for the black kids.

195
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:28,000
And so that was the vulnerable point.

196
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:34,000
But by this time, they decided they were going to change the strategy and start to attack segregation per se.

197
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:40,000
So in Farmville, that was one of the things he told the parents.

198
00:19:40,000 --> 00:19:48,000
Because the children organized this community meeting with parents and everybody for the lawyers to come in and talk.

199
00:19:48,000 --> 00:19:55,000
And one of the things he said was, you know, this is about desegregation per se, not just about separate but equal.

200
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:58,000
And kind of let them know what they would be in for.

201
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:02,000
Be a relatively long fight.

202
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:07,000
But the community was ready to support it.

203
00:20:07,000 --> 00:20:16,000
So that case, Davis v. County School Board of Prince Edward County, became one of the cases that was part of the Brown package.

204
00:20:16,000 --> 00:20:23,000
I guess it was alphabetical who was Brown, but where Brown gets the styling with.

205
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:27,000
Okay.

206
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:30,000
Okay.

207
00:20:30,000 --> 00:20:32,000
Okay.

208
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:34,000
So that was the Farmville.

209
00:20:34,000 --> 00:20:35,000
Farmville, yes.

210
00:20:35,000 --> 00:20:37,000
And then went on for quite some time.

211
00:20:37,000 --> 00:20:47,000
Well, this was I think 52 in Barbara Rose Johns first called him and it was 54 before the case was finally decided by the Supreme Court.

212
00:20:47,000 --> 00:20:50,000
Well, that time Barbara Rose Johns suffered a lot.

213
00:20:50,000 --> 00:20:58,000
She eventually had to leave Farmville because of the pressures that were mounting against her.

214
00:20:58,000 --> 00:21:10,000
She comes from an interesting family to her father was Reverend, I can't remember his first name, Andy.

215
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:11,000
Vernon Johns.

216
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:12,000
Was her uncle.

217
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:13,000
Vernon Johns was her uncle.

218
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:15,000
Yeah, the father's name I don't remember either.

219
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:34,000
And Vernon Johns who was in Petersburg for a while eventually went down to Alabama and he was at the church right before Martin Luther King came out of connections to Virginia to this early civil rights activity.

220
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:44,000
Although most people think the civil rights movement started in the 1950s, but you know, 30 years before they were starting these cases in the court.

221
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:57,000
In fact, 10 years before Rosa Parks, my father's firm had a case with Irene Morgan who was the same kind of story she refused to give a proceed on a bus.

222
00:21:57,000 --> 00:22:11,000
This was the interstate bus and eventually that case led to interstate segregation, interstate transportation being ruled illegal.

223
00:22:11,000 --> 00:22:13,000
Okay.

224
00:22:13,000 --> 00:22:20,000
So, yeah, there were a lot of precursors to Martin Luther King in the 50s.

225
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:26,000
And then the interstate travel law was one that they used testing that to push into the stuff.

226
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:27,000
With the freedom rights.

227
00:22:27,000 --> 00:22:28,000
Yeah.

228
00:22:28,000 --> 00:22:29,000
Very interesting.

229
00:22:29,000 --> 00:22:36,000
So did you get the sense from your father that he had a sense of this being incremental one step at a time kind of a...

230
00:22:36,000 --> 00:22:38,000
Yeah, for sure.

231
00:22:39,000 --> 00:22:47,000
And you know, from the time he left law school to the brown decision that was almost 20 some years.

232
00:22:47,000 --> 00:22:52,000
So they did see this as this incremental strategy.

233
00:22:52,000 --> 00:23:01,000
And again, changing strategy because they started out with attacking separate equal and then eventually attacking segregation itself.

234
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:11,000
And it was interesting because in those days because Richmond was segregated when the lawyers would come through town they would always stay with us because they couldn't stay in the hotels downtown.

235
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:19,000
There were a few black hotels around like Eglistan's and slaughters but they usually tend to stay with us.

236
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:25,000
So there would be these little strategies, sessions around the breakfast table and I would be off in the corner somewhere.

237
00:23:25,000 --> 00:23:29,000
I didn't know exactly what was going on but I just knew something important was happening.

238
00:23:29,000 --> 00:23:36,000
And you know, they're good Marshall and Robert L. Carter and some of the other lawyers would always be through town.

239
00:23:36,000 --> 00:23:39,000
So it was an interesting time.

240
00:23:39,000 --> 00:23:41,000
And your father's partner was Spottswood W. Robinson III.

241
00:23:41,000 --> 00:23:43,000
Spottswood W. Robinson III, right?

242
00:23:43,000 --> 00:23:45,000
And when did they start working together?

243
00:23:45,000 --> 00:23:54,000
Well, they started in the 40s and they continued to be partners through the 50s and then...

244
00:23:54,000 --> 00:24:06,000
Spottswood W. Robinson III went to Howard to be the dean of the law school and eventually a federal judge.

245
00:24:06,000 --> 00:24:20,000
One of the things that was interesting was that all the lawyers for the NAACP thought that once the Supreme Court made this decision that would be it, that would be the law of the land, everybody would comply.

246
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:23,000
The country would be changed.

247
00:24:23,000 --> 00:24:36,000
And of course Virginia led the push for massive resistance and to resist the desegregation order and who knows what kind of effect that had on the country.

248
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:45,000
We probably could be in the post-racial society.

249
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:53,000
But can you talk about some of the actual responses from the White community that made our massive resistance?

250
00:24:53,000 --> 00:25:02,000
Well, we're led by members of the Bird Machine in Virginia. The governor at the time was J. Lindsay Almond Jr.

251
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:06,000
So it was at the highest level that this resistance was coming.

252
00:25:07,000 --> 00:25:16,000
And you know, this was kind of unheard of that the governor and state legislatures were going to just defy the law.

253
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:26,000
And so a whole new set of cases had to start to be put together to try to force compliance.

254
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:31,000
And so I guess for the next 10 years or so, that was the nature of the cases.

255
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:38,000
I was in one of the first group of students in Virginia to desegregate the schools until the 1960s.

256
00:25:38,000 --> 00:25:42,000
So that was like seven years after the Brown decision.

257
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:47,000
And for most of Virginia, desegregation didn't come for another five or six years.

258
00:25:47,000 --> 00:25:51,000
So even here in Richmond, what level school was it that you were in?

259
00:25:51,000 --> 00:25:55,000
I was in junior high school at the time.

260
00:25:55,000 --> 00:25:59,000
And it was a court case that was brought?

261
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:05,000
Well, this was, it wasn't a specific case, but this was a continual fight that they had.

262
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:08,000
At those days, they had something called a pupil placement board.

263
00:26:08,000 --> 00:26:13,000
And a pupil placement board would decide what schools you would go to.

264
00:26:13,000 --> 00:26:26,000
And it was interesting though that head of the school board at that time was Louis Powell, who was a fairly progressive individual.

265
00:26:26,000 --> 00:26:31,000
He and my father had a really good relationship.

266
00:26:31,000 --> 00:26:42,000
And so he would always give my father an opportunity to speak before the school board and before other community groups.

267
00:26:42,000 --> 00:26:54,000
So, you know, there was a gradual trickle of black students that were starting to be allowed into the white schools.

268
00:26:54,000 --> 00:26:56,000
But it was definitely not integration.

269
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:59,000
And my father would say it was desegregation, but not integration.

270
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:02,000
It's just a token number of students.

271
00:27:02,000 --> 00:27:06,000
Can you tell us a little bit about what that difference is?

272
00:27:06,000 --> 00:27:08,000
Well, as you saw it as you saw it.

273
00:27:08,000 --> 00:27:11,000
As he saw it was mainly in terms of numbers.

274
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:18,000
If he had two black kids in a high school of 1,500, he wouldn't say that was an integrated school.

275
00:27:18,000 --> 00:27:21,000
It might be desegregated, but it's not integrated.

276
00:27:21,000 --> 00:27:28,000
Because I'm also, right now I'm looking at the military during the Korean War.

277
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:36,000
And it's the same thing when you say integrate the services and send a single black soldier to a white unit is that what is that?

278
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:37,000
Yeah, yeah.

279
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:46,000
But, you know, the military probably was one of the most progressive institutions in terms of eventual integration.

280
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:52,000
Once the presidential directive was given.

281
00:27:52,000 --> 00:27:55,000
But so that was your own case.

282
00:27:55,000 --> 00:27:58,000
So, your own experience?

283
00:27:58,000 --> 00:28:00,000
Yeah.

284
00:28:00,000 --> 00:28:08,000
So, you know, I really didn't want to be one of these students who was integrating.

285
00:28:08,000 --> 00:28:11,000
So, I wanted to go to the black schools with all my friends.

286
00:28:12,000 --> 00:28:18,000
You know, it was interesting that it was inevitable based on what my father was doing.

287
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:26,000
But they would do such ridiculous things as take out yardsticks and measure the distance from one school to another to try to keep kids out.

288
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:33,000
I can remember one friend of mine who wasn't allowed in Chandler Middle School, which was the white junior high school.

289
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:40,000
Because, Grey's, which was the black school, was three feet closer to his house than Chandler Middle School.

290
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:45,000
So, there's a lot of that kind of stuff going on.

291
00:28:45,000 --> 00:28:48,000
But eventually, you know, we did start to trickle in.

292
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:55,000
And so, I can remember the first day of going to the white junior high school.

293
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:09,000
And my father had been working in the Kennedy campaign and he got a job, but was given a job at the Federal Housing Administration during the Kennedy Administration.

294
00:29:09,000 --> 00:29:15,000
So, he was in Washington most of the week these days.

295
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:26,000
And I remember the first day of school I was given a ride with his new junior partner, Henry L. Marsh III, gave me a ride to school that morning.

296
00:29:26,000 --> 00:29:31,000
And I was walking up the steps. It was like the school was deserted out in front.

297
00:29:31,000 --> 00:29:36,000
There was nobody, no teachers, no movement, no nothing. It was me walking up these steps.

298
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:42,000
And then I went to the principal's office and there were other black kids there in the principal's office.

299
00:29:42,000 --> 00:29:45,000
And then they marched this out two by two to the different home rooms.

300
00:29:45,000 --> 00:29:51,000
You know, they kind of had this partial doubt around the school.

301
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:57,000
So, it was kind of an interesting, surrealistic day.

302
00:29:57,000 --> 00:29:58,000
And...

303
00:29:58,000 --> 00:30:01,000
Did no big backlash on that day?

304
00:30:01,000 --> 00:30:04,000
No big backlash on that day.

305
00:30:04,000 --> 00:30:15,000
You know, after a while, you started to sort things out. And you would know the kids in the areas where you would tend to get call NIGA or some other problem would happen.

306
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:19,000
And you would tend to avoid those situations as much as possible.

307
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:24,000
And of course the black kids mainly kept together.

308
00:30:24,000 --> 00:30:31,000
But over the years, gradually people started to get to know one another.

309
00:30:31,000 --> 00:30:38,000
And then when I was in the middle of the class, it was in the seventh grade then, kind of went all the way through high school.

310
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:43,000
And by the time I got to high school, I was on the football team.

311
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:48,000
And so, you know, the real problem kids were also on the football team.

312
00:30:48,000 --> 00:30:52,000
And so you kind of got to know them when they got to be teammates.

313
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:57,000
And it was kind of like, you know, the way in which people envision integration working.

314
00:30:57,000 --> 00:31:03,000
And you go together, you kind of acknowledge the humanity that you share.

315
00:31:03,000 --> 00:31:12,000
And even those who were most prejudiced at the seventh grade, were gradually, you know, starting to become at least friendly.

316
00:31:12,000 --> 00:31:14,000
If not friends.

317
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:16,000
By the time we got to high school.

318
00:31:16,000 --> 00:31:19,000
So changing minds one person at a time.

319
00:31:19,000 --> 00:31:20,000
Yeah.

320
00:31:20,000 --> 00:31:23,000
But of course, you had to take on when you're a teenager.

321
00:31:23,000 --> 00:31:25,000
Yeah, it is.

322
00:31:25,000 --> 00:31:39,000
And by the time I got to high school, well, maybe a year or two after I left high school, it was a black girl who was the prom queen in that same school.

323
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:44,000
So there really was, starting to be kind of even a little bit of a social integration in schools.

324
00:31:44,000 --> 00:31:48,000
When I was there, it was pretty still much social segregation.

325
00:31:48,000 --> 00:31:51,000
I mean, we ate together in the cafeteria.

326
00:31:51,000 --> 00:31:54,000
If we went to a dance at the high school, we would have our area.

327
00:31:54,000 --> 00:31:57,000
We would be dancing and they would have their area.

328
00:31:57,000 --> 00:32:00,000
But gradually, that started to change.

329
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:10,000
But of course, as soon as things started to gradually integrate, then you had to re-saggregation with the right flight with the busing that came in the late 1960s.

330
00:32:10,000 --> 00:32:18,000
So, you know, had the experiment continued, you know, again, things might be a little different now.

331
00:32:18,000 --> 00:32:21,000
And Richmond did experience a lot of that white flight.

332
00:32:21,000 --> 00:32:27,000
Oh, yeah. Once the busing was instituted as a remedy.

333
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:44,000
And one other courageous figure at that time was Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr, who was a local judge here in Richmond who ordered busing patterns that included the surrounding counties.

334
00:32:44,000 --> 00:33:04,000
And I mean, just to show how these little circumstances led to some really important ramifications.

335
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:08,000
That solution, you know, would have really had a big impact.

336
00:33:08,000 --> 00:33:13,000
We still have this tension between the city and the counties today.

337
00:33:13,000 --> 00:33:20,000
I mean, kind of a leftover from those old racial politics days.

338
00:33:20,000 --> 00:33:25,000
But Marriage was, you know, he also got a lot of threats.

339
00:33:25,000 --> 00:33:28,000
The dog was killed.

340
00:33:28,000 --> 00:33:32,000
You know, his children were threatened.

341
00:33:32,000 --> 00:33:42,000
And when the case went to, I don't know what circuit it was, but it was overturned.

342
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:44,000
And then it went to the Supreme Court.

343
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:56,000
And the Supreme Court then Nixon had just nominated the former Chief Justice.

344
00:33:56,000 --> 00:33:59,000
So, who was his name?

345
00:33:59,000 --> 00:34:02,000
I'm in a senior moment here.

346
00:34:02,000 --> 00:34:04,000
A William Rehnquist.

347
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:13,000
And also he had tried to nominate G. Harrold Carswell, but that didn't, that was blocked by the Senate.

348
00:34:13,000 --> 00:34:16,000
And so he nominated Lewis F. Powell Jr.

349
00:34:16,000 --> 00:34:21,000
And Lewis F. Powell Jr and William Rehnquist got on the bench.

350
00:34:21,000 --> 00:34:26,000
They hadn't heard the original arguments for this case.

351
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:30,000
And Powell, because of his previous association with the Richmond School,

352
00:34:30,000 --> 00:34:32,000
what recused himself.

353
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:34,000
And William Rehnquist didn't.

354
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:44,000
And so the Supreme Court had a 4-4 split, which meant that the lower court finding was upheld.

355
00:34:44,000 --> 00:34:50,000
And so the inclusion of the counties in the busing plan, you know, fell through.

356
00:34:50,000 --> 00:34:56,000
But Powell not recused himself or had William Rehnquist recused himself.

357
00:34:56,000 --> 00:35:01,000
This might be a different world now.

358
00:35:01,000 --> 00:35:03,000
But anyway, you know-

359
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:08,000
I've done some work in Louisville, which is interesting because they just, at the same time that they passed busing,

360
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:11,000
they collapsed, they just collapsed County and city government into one.

361
00:35:11,000 --> 00:35:12,000
Yeah.

362
00:35:12,000 --> 00:35:13,000
There's one way to get around that.

363
00:35:13,000 --> 00:35:14,000
Yeah.

364
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:17,000
Because Richmond is really interesting in the way racial politics works.

365
00:35:17,000 --> 00:35:25,000
At first, once in the late 60s and early 70s, when you did have this white flight,

366
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:28,000
of course, now you had much more black political power in Richmond.

367
00:35:28,000 --> 00:35:38,000
And so the white political structure in Richmond started to annex territory from the surrounding counties.

368
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:47,000
And that was eventually blocked by the federal government based on the Voting Rights Act, because it was an attempt to dilute the black, the strengths of the black vote.

369
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:50,000
So they couldn't annex anymore.

370
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:53,000
So now, you had continued white flight.

371
00:35:53,000 --> 00:36:01,000
And now the legislature, once Richmond annexation moratorium.

372
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:06,000
So as land locked, all the tax base was moving out to the counties.

373
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:11,000
And this is a pattern that you see over and over again in cities.

374
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:18,000
But Richmond in Virginia is unique, and usually you do have cities embedded in a county.

375
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:20,000
But in Richmond, you have these independent cities.

376
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:27,000
And so, you know, even to this day, the same struggles between the counties and the cities are there.

377
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:32,000
Now it's clothed more in class kinds of issues.

378
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:40,000
The race issue morphed into a class issue, because you had a lot of black flight too, black middle class flight.

379
00:36:40,000 --> 00:36:43,000
But in your opinion, the race issue is still embedded in there?

380
00:36:43,000 --> 00:36:50,000
Oh, it's still in there, yeah. But it's kind of tamped down.

381
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:54,000
I mean, close the door.

382
00:36:54,000 --> 00:36:56,000
We'll back.

383
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:06,000
Or you mentioned this a little bit, but were you a little bit miffed at your dad that are your folks that you were put forth as an experimenter?

384
00:37:06,000 --> 00:37:14,000
I was a little bit miffed, but I kind of recognized that the cause was good.

385
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:30,000
And, you know, I still had a lot of social connections to the kids going to the black schools, because that was still our social group.

386
00:37:30,000 --> 00:37:31,000
How did you get to school?

387
00:37:31,000 --> 00:37:34,000
Yeah, I mean, you talked about the first day, but how did you get to school during the rest of your career?

388
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:37,000
Most of the time I walked. It really wasn't a Chandler Middle School.

389
00:37:37,000 --> 00:37:47,000
We lived in Northside over here on Overbrook Road, and it was just about maybe eight or ten blocks from Chandler Middle School.

390
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:50,000
And then after high school, you went on to...

391
00:37:50,000 --> 00:37:53,000
I went to Howard University.

392
00:37:53,000 --> 00:38:06,000
And that was an interesting time too, in the late 60s, because I had a bit of political activity and black power and African history and all these things that were still there.

393
00:38:06,000 --> 00:38:10,000
That were starting to emerge.

394
00:38:10,000 --> 00:38:21,000
And so, you know, for me, it was kind of a high opening time.

395
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:34,000
I was fortunate to have, for example, a history class with one of the imminent scholars on African history.

396
00:38:34,000 --> 00:38:40,000
Whose name just went out of my head, but I think I would have had a minute.

397
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:54,000
But I had never heard anything about Africa up until that time, other than Tarzan movies, but nothing in terms of any kind of African civilizations or any of that kind of thing.

398
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:08,000
So that was eye-opening. And of course, there were a lot of, you know, black revolutionaries on campus, Stokely Carmichael and H.R.F. Brown, the idea of black power.

399
00:39:08,000 --> 00:39:23,000
So there was definitely a change starting to happen then from Martin Luther King, non-violent protest, kind of passive protest, the idea of integration to the idea of...

400
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:31,000
You know, kind of black nationalism kind of thing among the black intellectuals at Howard.

401
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:34,000
And where was your mind then?

402
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:39,000
My mind was, you know, I was kind of persuaded by that argument.

403
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:44,000
I mean, most of it was kind of just rebellion of what I was familiar with.

404
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:49,000
Didn't want to be a black bourgeoisie anymore.

405
00:39:49,000 --> 00:39:58,000
So, you know, that might have held sway for a year or two, but...

406
00:39:58,000 --> 00:40:07,000
Gradually, I mean, I'm thinking of kind of moving in other directions.

407
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:13,000
This is when I first started to get interested in Eastern philosophy and meditation and things like that.

408
00:40:14,000 --> 00:40:29,000
And I think that was kind of a, you know, I can see it as a continuum of my experience as a child growing up in the segregated south, that you really have to do a lot of introspection and...

409
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:38,000
You have to really think about your sense of self in terms of, you know, these people don't like me because of skin color.

410
00:40:38,000 --> 00:40:44,000
And it causes, you know, a lot of those kinds of self-increased occur.

411
00:40:44,000 --> 00:40:53,000
And that continued and eventually in college, it took a more inward turn.

412
00:40:53,000 --> 00:41:01,000
And I found that some of these books in the Indian philosophy really spoke to me.

413
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:10,000
I wasn't... I was a history major, but as a senior, I took a course in perception in psychology.

414
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:25,000
And that also had a big influence on me, the idea that in many ways we construct reality, you know, based on our expectancies and our beliefs and our previous experiences.

415
00:41:26,000 --> 00:41:35,000
So that's, you know, it was too late to change my major then, but I did go into psychology and graduate school.

416
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:54,000
But in between graduating from university and going to grad school, I studied meditation more and became a meditation teacher first in Boston and then Detroit.

417
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:59,000
And that's, I got to University of Michigan.

418
00:42:01,000 --> 00:42:19,000
It's interesting to think about it. And you're really putting that together, the idea, you know, I often think about in practicing the strategy of non-violence in particular or just handling one's self with dignity and trying to be non-reactive or thoughtful about one's reaction.

419
00:42:19,000 --> 00:42:22,000
That's really is a process of mindfulness.

420
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:23,000
Yeah, it is.

421
00:42:23,000 --> 00:42:28,000
And you were really, you were already thinking in those terms back then.

422
00:42:28,000 --> 00:42:30,000
By the time I got to college, yeah.

423
00:42:30,000 --> 00:42:37,000
Well, by the time I started, this was kind of late in my college career, I started discovering Indian philosophy.

424
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:48,000
I kind of, you know, heard about Gandhi and knew he had some influence on King, but I really didn't know that much about Gandhi's story or...

425
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:54,000
Well, other aspects of Indian philosophy or hemsa, what, you know, what that meant.

426
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:59,000
Were there others at Howard that were getting into this or were you considered an apple?

427
00:42:59,000 --> 00:43:01,000
I was pretty out there by myself.

428
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:06,000
I mean, meditation is very mainstream these days.

429
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:08,000
But not in those days.

430
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:10,000
Yeah, not so much.

431
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:11,000
There you go.

432
00:43:11,000 --> 00:43:13,000
So then on to Michigan, you said?

433
00:43:13,000 --> 00:43:14,000
Yeah.

434
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:19,000
There was one other point I wanted to make though about my early years.

435
00:43:19,000 --> 00:43:27,000
When I was in those segregated schools in Richmond growing up, the quality of the teachers was just amazing.

436
00:43:27,000 --> 00:43:32,000
I mean, there were some kind of unintended consequences of integration.

437
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:38,000
I think one of the losses was the quality of the black teachers that we had in those classrooms.

438
00:43:38,000 --> 00:43:41,000
Women for the most part.

439
00:43:42,000 --> 00:43:48,000
And so again, this is another kind of confluence of things, but you know, the women's movement was very big in the 60s also.

440
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:52,000
And so at one time, all the best and brightest women went into teaching.

441
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:58,000
And so now they had wider possibilities.

442
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:04,000
And we didn't really put anything in place to attract the best and brightest into education anymore.

443
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:12,000
And I think black education has suffered more than education in general because of these other influence of white,

444
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:19,000
white, tax-based, erosion, poor resources in the inner cities.

445
00:44:19,000 --> 00:44:25,000
I mean, I now work a lot with Petersburg.

446
00:44:25,000 --> 00:44:30,000
And they have the lowest performing schools in the state.

447
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:35,000
It's kind of a desperate situation.

448
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:40,000
They lost their tax-based number of years ago and tobacco companies moved out.

449
00:44:40,000 --> 00:44:44,000
I just saw yesterday they get ready to lose a chemical plant too.

450
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:58,000
But when you have a school district like that, it becomes this spiraling kind of downward pattern.

451
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:03,000
Because even if you get some decent teachers, they immediately get recruited away.

452
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:10,000
Because they can make more money at surrounding districts and have half the headaches.

453
00:45:10,000 --> 00:45:17,000
And so it becomes very difficult to recruit people into those kinds of school districts and administrators.

454
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:27,000
Since I started working with the schools in 2005 and they've been four superintendents in that time in Petersburg.

455
00:45:28,000 --> 00:45:34,000
Was there something lost to you think when the schools desegregated with the talk about administrators,

456
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:42,000
the black principals and some of the black teachers that had been working in a black school system and as things change, and what happens to them?

457
00:45:42,000 --> 00:45:50,000
Yeah. And most of the principals were not given principalships again when things integrated.

458
00:45:51,000 --> 00:46:02,000
The teachers, I mean, for one thing, most of the black educators during the era of segregation kind of saw themselves on a mission.

459
00:46:02,000 --> 00:46:09,000
The education was the key for upward mobility and that would be driven in.

460
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:15,000
And again, you didn't have this kind of class segregation that we have now in the black schools.

461
00:46:16,000 --> 00:46:21,000
Because kids from middle class, lower middle class, everybody was there in the same school.

462
00:46:21,000 --> 00:46:26,000
And so there was a sense of kind of shared values and things that we get inculcated.

463
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:32,000
Whereas now, you know, the black middle classes out in the suburbs with the white middle class.

464
00:46:32,000 --> 00:46:44,000
So in the inner city, you mainly have, you know, kind of these hubs of poverty and, you know, lack of role models, lack of resources.

465
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:54,000
So now it becomes sort of, those are different people entirely and that's their problem in front of the point of view of those in the summer.

466
00:46:54,000 --> 00:47:04,000
And again, it still has a strong racial component to that, but you do have class kind of overlaying with that as well.

467
00:47:04,000 --> 00:47:07,000
And is that in the case here in Richmond?

468
00:47:07,000 --> 00:47:09,000
Oh, definitely.

469
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:20,000
I mean, I think that's one of the main things holding Richmond back is this lack of cooperation between the city and the surrounding counties.

470
00:47:22,000 --> 00:47:28,000
And, you know, if you talk to the leaders in the counties, none of them would say race has anything to do with it these days.

471
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:35,000
But the seeds of this were definitely in the racial politics, you know, even though it's morphed into other things these days.

472
00:47:36,000 --> 00:47:46,000
How has Richmond recognized its change in the legacy of the movement and has Richmond recognized your father's contribution?

473
00:47:46,000 --> 00:47:49,000
Yeah, Richmond has.

474
00:47:49,000 --> 00:48:03,000
We had a succession of governors that have attempted to, you know, kind of add the black story to Virginia history.

475
00:48:04,000 --> 00:48:10,000
There was another thing that was interesting when I first went to white schools and we would take a Virginia history class.

476
00:48:10,000 --> 00:48:19,000
And when you read about slavery, it was such a benign institution, you know, they were just like family members, you know, everybody loved everybody.

477
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:26,000
Even from my brief experience, knew that was a lot of crap.

478
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:30,000
That was what was being taught.

479
00:48:30,000 --> 00:48:42,000
And so you can understand why, you know, the larger white community doesn't understand what the problem is or why we still talking about slavery 150 years later.

480
00:48:45,000 --> 00:48:50,000
So I forgot your question, but...

481
00:48:51,000 --> 00:49:04,000
If Virginia and Richmond in particular have tried to correct things in some way or at least made a, you know, a semblance of trying to, and have they recognized the movement and your father?

482
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:19,000
I think, you know, this started with the election of L. Douglas Wilder and you had George Allen in there, but there's been a succession of democratic governors who have attempted to do this.

483
00:49:20,000 --> 00:49:27,000
And they were able to acknowledge the black contribution to Virginia history and particularly the civil rights history.

484
00:49:27,000 --> 00:49:38,000
In the 40s and 50s and 60s, more cases, civil rights cases were brought in Richmond, I mean, in Virginia than any other southern state.

485
00:49:38,000 --> 00:49:40,000
And...

486
00:49:40,000 --> 00:49:43,000
What is that? I mean...

487
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:45,000
The father of Mr. Robinson.

488
00:49:45,000 --> 00:49:52,000
Well, yeah, I guess they were just kind of active, but, you know, there was kind of a climate here.

489
00:49:52,000 --> 00:50:01,000
There was a willingness to make that sacrifice among the populace.

490
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:08,000
And probably it might have been that Virginia, you know, for all of his problems was never Mississippi, you know.

491
00:50:08,000 --> 00:50:20,000
I mean, even though we had lynchings here and we had problems, and again, Barbara Rose Johns got run out of Farm Bill, you didn't have that constant kind of balance that you had further in the south.

492
00:50:20,000 --> 00:50:30,000
So maybe that created a climate where people felt a little safer to come forward and stand up against some of these segregation laws.

493
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:33,000
That's the possibility.

494
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:41,000
So more monuments and things like that began to appear on the landscape to recognize that there was more than civil war generals.

495
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:43,000
Right.

496
00:50:43,000 --> 00:50:49,000
Well, first it was the Arthur Ashe statue and that caused a big uproar.

497
00:50:49,000 --> 00:50:54,000
Can briefly, can you tell us a little bit about, you know, just for the record, because I think it's an interesting story.

498
00:50:54,000 --> 00:50:57,000
The monument avenue, what monuments were there.

499
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:07,000
Well, monument avenue was an avenue of monuments to Confederate generals and for the most part.

500
00:51:07,000 --> 00:51:17,000
And so you have, and the statues, you know, are huge statues, particularly of Robert E. Lee.

501
00:51:17,000 --> 00:51:25,000
The statues be facing a certain direction. They were facing the south if they survived the war. They're facing north if they were killed in the war.

502
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:30,000
So it's a very stately street.

503
00:51:30,000 --> 00:51:39,000
And so then the proposal came to erect a statue to Arthur Ashe and it was decided by the city council to put it on monument avenue.

504
00:51:39,000 --> 00:51:48,000
And of course, a lot of people came out of the woodwork complaining about this, that was kind of a sacrilege.

505
00:51:48,000 --> 00:52:01,000
I mean, it's so interesting. And I think one of the reasons Virginia is changing is because kind of the old Gentile Virginia, which was never as overtly racist as people further south.

506
00:52:01,000 --> 00:52:06,000
But it was still re-retired every now and then with these kind of things.

507
00:52:06,000 --> 00:52:17,000
I mean, there was a big objection to putting a statue of Lincoln at the Tredegar Iron Works, which was a building left over from the Civil War.

508
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:22,000
But, and this was like 10 years ago, 15 years ago.

509
00:52:22,000 --> 00:52:31,000
And it was an objection to a statue of Lincoln, you know, these days. It's just unbelievable.

510
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:35,000
But as heritage not hate you.

511
00:52:35,000 --> 00:52:40,000
Well, I wouldn't be in Virginia, too. And especially in Southwest Virginia, it can be pretty wacky sometimes.

512
00:52:40,000 --> 00:52:45,000
People are really still playing a little violent in about the war.

513
00:52:45,000 --> 00:52:52,000
Yeah, I mean, it's the war that never ends. In the South where rise again.

514
00:52:52,000 --> 00:52:53,000
Okay.

515
00:52:53,000 --> 00:52:59,000
So as a kid going downtown, these were the figures that towered over you.

516
00:52:59,000 --> 00:53:04,000
And then Ashe was added and others.

517
00:53:04,000 --> 00:53:23,000
Well, others yet on monument avenue. But they did put in this memorial to Virginia Civil Rights history on the Capitol grounds, which pictures Barbara Rose Johns on one side and my father and Robinson on one side.

518
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:30,000
And it's just an acknowledgement of Virginia's role in the Civil Rights movement.

519
00:53:30,000 --> 00:53:37,000
And of course, it's right down from a statue of Harry F. Byrd Sr. It's an interesting juxtaposition.

520
00:53:37,000 --> 00:53:44,000
And also they named a building from my father on the Capitol grounds, the old finance building.

521
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:58,000
And there's an irony about that, too, because that was the place where Bird and some of the others kind of worked out their initial strategy for massive resistance.

522
00:53:58,000 --> 00:54:08,000
And it was also a building where when my father graduated from law school, he went there to take the bar exam.

523
00:54:08,000 --> 00:54:17,000
And of course, the seating was segregated and he came in late. And the only city saw was up front, which was in the white section. So he wouldn't sit down there.

524
00:54:17,000 --> 00:54:21,000
And it was a bit of a ral, but I think they eventually let him sit there.

525
00:54:21,000 --> 00:54:26,000
And so all that's in that same building.

526
00:54:26,000 --> 00:54:32,000
But seeing his name on it must people don't know those back stories.

527
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:37,000
And nationally, how has your father and his work been recognized?

528
00:54:37,000 --> 00:54:47,000
Well, in the last 10 years of his life, he lived to be a hundred. And so the last 10 years of his life, he did get a lot of national recognition, which was good.

529
00:54:47,000 --> 00:55:02,000
And he was able to get that before he died. And in 1999, President Clinton gave him the presidential medal of freedom, which was the highest civilian honor.

530
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:05,000
Is it in the middle there?

531
00:55:05,000 --> 00:55:06,000
Yes.

532
00:55:06,000 --> 00:55:09,000
Is it possible to get a shot of the...

533
00:55:09,000 --> 00:55:11,000
Okay, we're going over for a shot.

534
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:20,000
This will take a little... I'm just going to let the camera run and do it.

535
00:55:20,000 --> 00:55:25,000
So that's the presidential medal of freedom that was awarded in 2009.

536
00:55:25,000 --> 00:55:29,000
That's now you know.

537
00:55:29,000 --> 00:55:32,000
And is that your father's foster?

538
00:55:32,000 --> 00:55:34,000
Yes.

539
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:41,000
Okay.

540
00:55:41,000 --> 00:55:44,000
Is this getting a second to get a shot of that?

541
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:46,000
Just want to make sure we have a shot of that.

542
00:55:46,000 --> 00:55:48,000
That would bring in if need be.

543
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:51,000
That's great.

544
00:55:57,000 --> 00:55:59,000
Okay, I think we can keep going.

545
00:55:59,000 --> 00:56:00,000
Okay.

546
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:14,000
So I want to shift to asking you about your career in psychology and how some of these concerns interest themes may have played into your work.

547
00:56:14,000 --> 00:56:15,000
Yeah.

548
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:24,000
Well, my whole career has been at Virginia State University, which is a historically black university.

549
00:56:24,000 --> 00:56:32,000
So, you know, just kind of being in that environment, you reminded of all of this history.

550
00:56:32,000 --> 00:56:42,000
Because Virginia State and most of the other HBCUs were founded to provide an opportunity for blacks and states to have a higher education.

551
00:56:42,000 --> 00:56:45,000
They didn't want them to come to the white institutions.

552
00:56:46,000 --> 00:56:57,000
And you know, our colors are orange and blue because we used to get hand me downs from UVA for football, other things.

553
00:56:57,000 --> 00:56:59,000
I didn't know that.

554
00:56:59,000 --> 00:57:00,000
That was why.

555
00:57:00,000 --> 00:57:02,000
Interesting.

556
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:17,000
And, you know, over the years, it's been interesting to see the politics around, you know, state allocations for our education with VSU.

557
00:57:17,000 --> 00:57:24,000
In Virginia, you know, we have a system unlike many states.

558
00:57:24,000 --> 00:57:27,000
I mean, North Carolina, you have one state system in Virginia.

559
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:29,000
We have tech and UVA.

560
00:57:29,000 --> 00:57:38,000
And then we have, kind of a second tier now, VCU in George Mason, maybe, and then the rest of us.

561
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:50,000
But, you know, so just being in that setting, you know, just kind of creates a lot of reminders of those kinds of things.

562
00:57:50,000 --> 00:58:00,000
And a lot of my research has been done on black education and cognitive factors.

563
00:58:00,000 --> 00:58:16,000
And it's been interesting, you know, looking at this thing about US education and, you know, thinking from brown forward,

564
00:58:16,000 --> 00:58:35,000
how the current state is really the latest iteration of those same issues that was there 50 or 60 years ago.

565
00:58:35,000 --> 00:58:50,000
And now, of course, we know about the effect of nutrition on education and our early childhood medical attention and cognitive stimulation.

566
00:58:50,000 --> 00:59:08,000
One of the things that is definitely a key element of the lagging of black educational achievement nationwide is this lack of early childhood stimulation.

567
00:59:08,000 --> 00:59:18,000
But we know now that these cognitive abilities that in the 50s were thought to be totally fixed all heredity.

568
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:28,000
We know they're malleable and that with the right kinds of experiences, you can start to develop these skills.

569
00:59:28,000 --> 00:59:35,000
That's been something that I've been interested in working with the last 10 or 15 years or so.

570
00:59:35,000 --> 00:59:42,000
And that's how I got first in contact with Algebra Project and Bob Moses + Algebra Project.

571
00:59:42,000 --> 00:59:48,000
We set up a project in Petersburg and they came in.

572
00:59:48,000 --> 01:00:03,000
Bob Moses + Algebra Project was an early civil rights leader in the 1960s and he's involved in a lot of the voter registration programs, things that went on in Mississippi.

573
01:00:03,000 --> 01:00:15,000
And then he later got a PhD in math from Harvard and he was dissatisfied with the way in which his own kids were experiencing math in Cambridge schools.

574
01:00:15,000 --> 01:00:27,000
So he developed these approaches to teaching abstract mathematical concepts in ways that are based on experiences, the life experiences of children.

575
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:32,000
And he's been very successful in doing that.

576
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:43,000
But he also takes a civil rights approach to school reform in that he uses the same kind of principles of community organization around support for schools.

577
01:00:43,000 --> 01:00:51,000
That it's not just the schools or the teachers by themselves that can bring about change, but it takes a whole community effort.

578
01:00:51,000 --> 01:00:54,000
Can bring in the parents and the community.

579
01:00:54,000 --> 01:00:57,000
Exactly.

580
01:00:57,000 --> 01:01:00,000
So that's been very interesting.

581
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:11,000
And that connects back to your experience, the way that you read about slavery, what you said before, the kinds of materials that are presented to students.

582
01:01:11,000 --> 01:01:23,000
We did an interview with a woman in California, Mildred Pitts Walter, who was an educator in the Los Angeles system in the 40s and 50s.

583
01:01:23,000 --> 01:01:32,000
She was looking for story books with black kids in them to teach the black kids in her class and there were no such things.

584
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:35,000
So she wrote her own.

585
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:38,000
And made it into a career.

586
01:01:38,000 --> 01:01:41,000
But it's interesting that kind of thing.

587
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:44,000
So what kind of effects can that have?

588
01:01:44,000 --> 01:01:49,000
Can you measure and see a change when you do introduce materials like that?

589
01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:51,000
Yes, you can.

590
01:01:51,000 --> 01:01:54,000
One of the things that we're always looking for is transfer.

591
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:11,000
If you work in the cognitive domain and you're trying to develop cognitive skills per se, through practice of things like attention and short-term memory and those kinds of activities, do you get transfer to performance in math or other things?

592
01:02:11,000 --> 01:02:13,000
We find that you do.

593
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:21,000
You do need content as well, but it's like the cognitive training is like building the framework.

594
01:02:21,000 --> 01:02:24,000
And then you still need the content to fit into that framework.

595
01:02:24,000 --> 01:02:28,000
But without the framework, there's nothing for the content to adhere to.

596
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:40,000
And so students in general today tend to, you know, even high-performing students tend to have all these unorganized concepts that aren't integrated in any kind of way.

597
01:02:40,000 --> 01:02:45,000
Aren't able to do any kind of abstraction from those concepts.

598
01:02:45,000 --> 01:02:55,000
And a lot of it is from the lack of that development of underlying cognitive framework.

599
01:02:55,000 --> 01:03:05,000
And, you know, in general, there's kind of been a dumbing down of education in the country over the years.

600
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:18,000
When I went to Chandler Middle School when I was 12 or 13, I mean, this might seem just being apparent reality because of my advancing age.

601
01:03:18,000 --> 01:03:26,000
But it seems as if the educational rigor was higher than it is with college kids these days.

602
01:03:26,000 --> 01:03:35,000
And in terms of both the breadth and the depth of information that we were exposed to.

603
01:03:35,000 --> 01:03:46,000
And I think part of that is in terms of the teacher pool, I think part of it is in terms of educational experience.

604
01:03:46,000 --> 01:04:04,000
I think part of it is some unintended consequences from well-meaning liberal teachers who didn't have the right level of expectation for black students.

605
01:04:04,000 --> 01:04:07,000
My mother was an educator for years.

606
01:04:07,000 --> 01:04:18,000
I can remember her saying that in the 60s when they started to have the integrated schools that these teachers weren't holding the kids to the same stand as the black teachers were holding the kids to.

607
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:26,000
And so there was this, I mean, George Bush, you know, I don't agree with him on very many things.

608
01:04:26,000 --> 01:04:38,000
When he came up with one phrase I thought was pretty apt and that was, and I can't remember the phrase now, but it was something about the high prejudices of low expectations or something like that.

609
01:04:38,000 --> 01:04:52,000
And I think that's true that, you know, the self-esteem movement and the social passing movement, I don't know if you can call them movements, but it tends to be trends in education.

610
01:04:52,000 --> 01:05:05,000
I think I've done a lot of damage and I think a lot of that came from well-meaning people worried about the ability of these poor little black kids in a city and what they couldn't could not do.

611
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:18,000
And most of the studies you read about minority education that works instead of dumbing down a curriculum to remediate any lacking information,

612
01:05:18,000 --> 01:05:27,000
is producing a challenging curriculum, you know, producing something that's going to stretch their capabilities.

613
01:05:27,000 --> 01:05:32,000
And students tend to respond to expectations.

614
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:42,000
But how challenging is that, especially in state of Virginia, and given our ironically named SOLs, our standards of learning,

615
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:46,000
to really affect change in both the curriculum and in the pedagogy?

616
01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:52,000
It's extremely challenging and that's been one of the problems with a school district like Petersburg.

617
01:05:52,000 --> 01:06:00,000
It's hard to come in and try to institute some innovation when everything is about the test scores.

618
01:06:00,000 --> 01:06:15,000
And you know, when the curriculum is so drained of any kind of intellectually stimulating content is all about performance on the test.

619
01:06:15,000 --> 01:06:29,000
And I think the lower performing schools disproportionately affects them in terms of how they spend their resources and their time.

620
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:43,000
